(e) (3 marks)

Here are the commands that I used to create fnmfres.Rdatastudents are not required to have shown/run this part.

#might have taken up to 25 minutes...
###NMF work
#x: the non-negative data (if any negatives exist, the whole data is shifted)
#q: the number of factors
#eps: convergence criteria (lack of progress on sum squared error)
#maxit: convergence criteria (max iteration when lack of progress not met)
#w: n by q loadings on factors (amount of chemical/molecule/etc)
#h: q by p observed factors (basis chemical/molecule/etc spectra)
#By default (when w, h NULL) both w and h are initialized randomly
nmf <- function(x, q, eps=0.0000001, maxit=2000, w=NULL, h=NULL){
  n <- nrow(x)
  p <- ncol(x)
  if(any(x<0)){x <- as.matrix(x)+abs(min(x))}
  else{x <- as.matrix(x)}
  if(is.null(w)){
    w <- matrix(runif(n*q, min(x), max(x)), n, q)
  }
  if(is.null(h)){
    h <- matrix(runif(p*q, min(x), max(x)), q, p)
  }
  ed <- sum((x-w%*%h)^2)
  conv <- FALSE
  ctr <- 1
  while(!conv){
    ctr <- ctr+1
    h <- h * (t(w) %*% x) / (t(w) %*% w %*% h) 
    w <- w * (x %*% t(h)) / (w %*% h %*% t(h))
    h[is.nan(h)] <- 0
    w[is.nan(w)] <- 0
    wh <- w%*%h
    ed[ctr] <- sum((x-wh)^2)
    if((ed[ctr-1]-ed[ctr] < eps)|(ctr==maxit)){
      conv <- TRUE
    }
  }
  list(ed=ed, w=w, h=h, x=x)
}
set.seed(5213541)
test <- nmf(immat+0.01, 25, maxit=600)

If they implemented their own version of the above, its likely the bases will differ at least in ordering!

Students are expected to have run/shown something along these lines

load("~/Downloads/fnmfres.Rdata")
par(mfrow=c(5,5), omi=c(0,0,0,0), mai=c(0.1,0.1,0.1,0.1))
for(i in 1:25){
  image((matrix(fnmfres$h[i,], 28, 28)), col=gray((0:32)/32), xaxt="n", yaxt="n")
}

These bases are made up much more of what could be thought of individual elements of fashion items. We can likely pick out several bases and give them a distinct name like long sleeves or high heel boot. In contrast, the eigenvectors looked more like layers of items within each principal component. For example, the first principal component looks like a bright long sleeve t-shirt with a dark sneaker overlaid on top of it. As we get further into the eigenvectors, they are less and less interpretable.

Note for students: the original MNIST handwritten digits data set also illustrates this type of result. The eigenvectors look like strange warping images that vaguely resemble bits and pieces of a digit overlaid on top of one another, while the NMF results look like individual pen strokes necessary to draw a number. It is both a constraint (only additive building allowed) and a lack of constraint (correlation among bases permitted) in NMF that lends itself to finding bases like this. Bringing it back to our fashion example, you can easily see that the bases showing pieces of the fashion images have to be correlated to some extent. If I score high on basis 1 (lower part of long sleeves), then Ill probably score highly on something like basis 16 (upper collar and short sleeves of a shirt) and score very close to 0 on basis 11 (sneaker). In PCA the components have to be orthogonal/uncorrelated, in NMF they do not.
